#Text=Aiguille is a sharply pointed rock outcrop or peak, very often produced by intense frost action in mountainous regions, such as the Alps.
#Text=Dissolution is the process whereby a rock, or parts of a rock, combine with water to form a solution.
#Text=Dome dune is a low, circular or oval mound formed where dune height is inhibited by unobstructed strong winds.
#Text=Estuary is the seaward end of a river, opening towards the sea, typically through a funnel-shaped inlet, and usually subject to tidal movements and incursions of salt water from the sea.
#Text=Feeder beach is a beach that is artificially widened and nourishes downdrift beaches by natural littoral currents or forces.
#Text=Flash is a depression formed by subsidence, particularly as a result of the solution of evaporite beds.
#Text=Floodplain is a relatively flat alluvial landform, constructed largely by the flow regime of the present river and subject to flooding.
#Text=Terracette is a small terrace that forms a step on a hillside. They often occur in near parallel series running approximately along the contours of a hillslope.
#Text=Colloids are particles of organic and mineral substances that range in size from 1 to 100 nm.
#Text=Rills are tiny hillside channels a few centimetres wide and deep that are cut by ephemeral rivulets.
#Text=Cirques are typically armchair-shaped hollows that form in mountainous terrain.
#Text=Lunate features are fractures shaped like crescents with the concavity facing the direction of ice flow.
#Text=Geer moraines or washboard moraines are series of small and roughly parallel ridges of till that are ordinarily associated with lakes or former lakes.
#Text=Eskers are the chief landform created by subglacial meltwater and form by the infilling of subglacial or englacial channels or by sedimentation in supraglacial channels.
#Text=Icing blisters are ice mounds created by groundwater injected at high pressure between icing layers.
#Text=Thermokarst is irregular terrain characterized by topographic depressions with hummocks between them.
#Text=Solifluction is an important periglacial process and forms sheets, lobes, terraces, and ploughing boulders.
#Text=Dunes are collections of loose sand built piecemeal by the wind.
#Text=Blowouts are depressions created by the deflation of loose sand partly bound by plant roots.
#Text=Tombolos are wave-built ridges of beach material connecting islands to the mainland or islands to islands.
